An HTTP/1.0 access controller that authorises or refuses each request
on the basis of method and path, with a complete Article 12 audit
trail emitted by the binary itself — no external wrapper. GET requests
to paths under /public/ are allowed (200 with an "allowed" reason in
the body). Anything else is refused (403 with a reason naming the
specific criterion that failed: wrong method, or path outside the
allowlist). Every request — allowed or refused — produces one JSONL
line on the audit log. If the audit log cannot be written, the server
exits with status 1 rather than serve a request whose audit trail was
lost.

This is the AI Act high-risk gate pattern, expressed end-to-end in one
.verbose file: Article 13 disclosure (this paragraph + the rule's
@intention), Article 86 explanation (the resp.body the user receives
is the same text that lands in the audit log), Article 12 trail (the
log: block), and the fail-closed guarantee (on_error: abort).
